Dimer covering and Kasteleyn Matrix

张陈成 519071910091

Introduction

In this article, we mainly discuss the dimer covering problems on the tessellation of squares and introduce the Kasteleyn matrix. One simple question is to determined the number of schemes to cover a chess board (8×8 square) with a collection of dimers (1×2 rectangles) without overlaps. The classical dimer covering problem is discussed in section I, which ends up with the approximation that the number of dimer configurations on m×n chess board reaches e(G/π)mn.

Some of the properties of Kasteleyn matrix is discussed in Section II. Our main goal is to evaluate the approximation of inverse Kasteleyn matrix.

The Classical Dimer Covering Problem

Counting the dimer configurations

Let Gm,n denotes the number of schemes to cover the m×n board with non-overlapping dimers, equivalently, Gm,n is the number of perfect matching on the m×n grid graph. We assume m is multiple of 2 and denotes N as mn2.

One notice that such m×n grid graph is a bipartite, as is it shown in the chess board that each pair of squares (vertices in the graph) under the same colour is non-adjacent. Let W={Wk}k=1N, B={Bk}k=1N be the set of white and black vertices respectively in the given m×n grid graph. We also make the graph directed under the following construction.

Let K be a N×N​ matrix such that

kij={+w(Wi,Bj),if Wi→Bj,−w(Wi,Bj),if Wi←Bj,0,otherwise.

Here w(Wi,Bj) is the weight of edge Wi−Bj in the given grid graph. For simplicity (while giving consideration to phisical significance), we assume that all vertical edges are of the same weight, so are all horizontal edges.

Let E′ be a subset of edges in the grid graph. Whenever E′ is a dimer configuration, there exists a permutation σ∈SN such that E′={Wi,Bσ(i)}i=1N. One notices that

detK=∑σ∈SNsgn(σ)∏i=1Nki,σ(i),

where E′ runs over all possible dimer configuartion.

Under the given direction, we claim that for each dimer configuration E1′={Wi,Bσ1(i)}i=1N and E2′={Wi,Bσ2(i)}i=1N, we have

sgn(σ1)∏i=1Nsgn(ki,σ1(i))=sgn(σ2)∏i=1Nsgn(ki,σ2(i)).

For simplicity, we assume all edges are weighted 1 and to prove that

sgn(σ1σ2)∏i=1Nsgn(ki,σ1(i)ki,σ2(i))=1.

One notices the (adjoint) union of any two dimer configuration is the disjoint union of double edges and even circles.

One notice that

  • For each multiple edge {Wi,Bσℓ(i)}ℓ=1,2, we have ki,σ1(i)=ki,σ2(i).

  • For each even loop with length 2l, σ1−1∘σ2 restricted in this loop is a rotation with sign (−1)l+1. One observe that each square contains exaxtly odd number of B→W edges. Thus the sign of the product of ki,σ1(i)ki,σ2(i) equals the number of square inside the loop (the area under the curve) in the sense of modulus 2. Since there are exactly even number of inner points in the loop, the picks's lemma illustrates that

    Area=Inner points+Boundary points2−1.

    Thus

    sgn(σ1−1|c∘σ2|c)∏some circle csgn(ki,σ1(i)ki,σ2(i))=(−1)l+1⋅sgn(2l2−1)=1.

We conclude that for w≡1, |detK| is the number of possible dimer configuration, i.e., |detK|=Gm,n.

Determinant of Kasteleyn matrix

Let δkl be 0 whence l≠k, δll=1 for each l in the given index set. Thus

k(x1,y1),(x2,y2)=(δx1x2−1−δx1x2+1)δy1y2+(−1)x1(δy1y2−1−δy1y2+1)δx1x2.

One notices that K is mn2×mn2, we define the complement of K as

K~=(OK−KTO).

Here |detK~|=|detK|2. Let

Qm×m=(−1)x1(δx1x2−1−δx1x2+1),Rn×n=(δy1y2−1−δy1y2+1),Sm×m=diag((−1)x1).

Then

K~=(S⊗1n)(z1Q⊗1n+z21m⊗R).

Here z1 and z2 are the weight for horizontal and vertical weight, respectively.

Via the knowledge of Чебышёв polynomials, it directly follows that the eigenvalues of R and Q are {2icos⁡(πk/(n+1))}k=1n, {2cos⁡(πk/(m+1))}k=1m, respectively. Hence

|detK~|=∏p=1n∏q=1m|z1λq(Q)+z2λp(R)|=∏p=1n∏q=1m/2|(z1λq(Q))2−(z2λp(R))2|=2mn∏p=1n∏q=1m/2|(z1cos⁡πqm+1)2+(z2cos⁡πpn+1)2|.

As a result,

Gm,n=|detK~|z1=z2=1=2mn/2∏p=1n∏q=1m/2cos2⁡πqm+1+cos2⁡πpn+1.

The number for dimer configurations on a 8×8 chess board is 12988816.

The approximation formula

Let Zm,n be |det(K~)|. We define the average free energy as

f(z1,z2):=limm,n→∞1mnlog⁡Zm,n.

We shall prove such limit exists as m,n→∞.

By definition of Riemann's integration, we have

f(z1,z2)=−limm,n→∞log⁡2mn/2mnlog⁡∏p=1n∏q=1m/2(z1cos⁡πqm+1)2+(z2cos⁡πpn+1)2=−1π2∫0π/2dθ∫0π/2log⁡[4(z12cos2⁡θ+z22cos2⁡ϕ)]dϕ=−1π∫0π/2dθ[12log2⁡(2z2cos⁡θ)+1π∫0π/2log⁡(1+cos2⁡ϕ(z2z1)2cos2⁡θ)dϕ]=−1π∫0π/2dθ[log⁡(2z2cos⁡θ)+log⁡1+1+z12z22cos2⁡θ2]=−1π∫0π/2dθ(log⁡z1+log⁡(z2z1cos⁡θ+1+(z2z1)2cos2⁡θ)=−12log⁡z1−1π∫0π/2g(z2z1cos⁡θ)dθ.

Here

g(x)=log⁡(x+1+x2)=∑j=0∞(2jj)(−1)j(2j+1)22jx2j+1.

It follows that

∫0π/2g(z2/z1cos⁡θ)dθ=∑j=0∞∫0π/2(2jj)(−1)j(z2/z1)2j+1(2j+1)22jcos2j+1⁡θdθ=∑j=0∞(−1)j(2j+1)2(z2/z1)2j+1=∫0z1/z1arctan⁡ttdt=12i(Li2(iz1/z2)−Li2(−iz1/z2)).

Especially, let z1=z2=1​, we deduce that

f(1,1)=−1π∫01arctan⁡tt−dt=Gπ.

Here G is the Catalan constant.

Dimer configuration on toroidal boundary conditions

Furthermore, one may consider the dimer covering problem under the toroidal boundary conditions, that is, the square chess board embedded into a torus with its opposite sides identified.

The previous proof fails on the m×n torus torus, since two matchings may differ on a loop which goes around the torus, thus is not null-homologous. Indeed, the change of signs in K from one dimer configuration to the other one is a function in H1(T,Z/2Z).

In fact, we can obtain the desired result in the the following orientations:

As shown in the previous section, some circles occurs in the union of any two dimer configurations. Here D++ gives perseves the sign of circles that homotopy to a single point, while fails to perserve the other cases.

Let

  • Z00 denote the class of dimer configuration wrapping both the horizontal and vertical directions even number of times,
  • Z10 denote those wrapping horizontal and vertical directions odd and even number of times respectively,
  • so are Z01 and Z11.

Therefore, we have

{detK++=Z00−Z10−Z01−Z11,detK+−=Z00−Z10+Z01+Z11,detK−+=Z00+Z10−Z01+Z11,detK−−=Z00+Z10+Z01−Z11.

It yields that

Zm,n′=Z00+Z01+Z10+Z11=12(−detK+++detK+−+detK−−+detK++).

It is also clear that f(z1,z2) has the same limit as the planar case.

Height functions

The height function of a dimer configuration maps the vertices to Z, which is uniquely defined by the following rules:

  • When encircling in an black area counterclockwisely, the height ascends 1 when the edge lies in the boundary of some dimer; descends 3 otherwise.
  • When encircling in an white area clockwisely, the height ascends 1 when the edge lies in the boundary of some dimer; descends 3 otherwise.
  • Assume one given vertices is of zero height for reference.

Such function is well-defined for any possible scheme of dimer configuration. The height function on the boundary of the region is independent of the covering. One can see the boundary of m×n chess board is flat than that in a Aztec diamond, which leaves corners blank for some random dimer configurations.

The discrete analysis on dimer coverings

Under some subtle change in the previous proof, the number of dimer configurations on m×n square is the absolute value of the determinant of the adjacency matrix of the grid graph, where with horizontal edges weighted 1 and vertical edges weighted i(=−1). For instance, the adjacency matrix of the following weighted 2×3 chess board is

A(G)=(000i100001i100001ii100001i100001i000)

We call such adjacency matrix the Kasteleyn matrix (denoted by K) thenceforth.

K as dirac operator

Since K is the adjacency matrix of a bipartite, the v1,v2-th entry in K−1 is zero whenever v1 and x2 has different colours. For any black vertex w∈W, we define

Kf:=f(w+1)−f(w−1)+i(f(w+i)−f(w−i)).

Then Kf≡0 whenever (∂x+i∂yf)≡0. Here ∂x and ∂y are discrete derivatives, such f is called as discrete analytic.

One may observe that K∗K is a Laplacian, i.e.,

As a consequence, 4f(b)=∑ε=03f(b+2iε), which is called the discrete mean value theorem.

The Green function is defined as ΔG(u,v)=δuv. Since

ΔK−1(w,⋅)=K∗KK−1(w,⋅)=(K∗δw)(⋅)=∑ε=03iεδw+iε―=∑ε=03(−i)εδw+iε,

K−1 is the sum of 4 Green functions.

K−1 on bounded domains

Let 2ϵZ2 be the discrete approximations of a Jordan domain Ω. Let Ωϵ:=ϵZ2∩Ω. The revised Ωϵ′ is obtained from Ωϵ by deleting the black vertices in Ωϵ lying in the outer face of Ω2ϵ. Therefore, Ωϵ has the same number of black and white vertices.

Other constructions can also be utilised while ensuring the discretisation of Ω has the same number of black and white vertices.

Let G(u,v) be the continuous Dirichlet Freen's function on Ω, G~(u,⋅) be the (analytic) complexification of G(u,⋅) such that Re(G~(u,⋅))=G(u,⋅)​. Then

K−1=2ϵdG~(u,v)+o(ϵ)=:12(F0(u,v)dux+iF1(u,v)duy)=:14(F+(u,v)du+F−(u,v)du―).

Let B0 (B1) be the set black vertices with vertices in even (odd) coordinates, Wi be the 1-grid shift vertically of Bi for i=1,2. Therefore, for |w−b|≫1 we have

K−1(w,b)={ϵ⋅ReF0(w,b)+o(ϵ)(w,b)∈W0×B0,ϵ⋅iImF0(w,b)+o(ϵ)(w,b)∈W0×B1,ϵ⋅ReF1(w,b)+o(ϵ)(w,b)∈W1×B0,ϵ⋅iImF1(w,b)+o(ϵ)(w,b)∈W1×B1.

For w∈W,b∈B such that |w−b|≫ϵ, we shall compare the Green function on R2 (for instance), i.e.,

G~(u,v)=−12πlog⁡(v−u),dG~(u,v)=12πdux+iduyv−u.

Here F0=F1=1π(v−u). For the comformal mapping ϕ:U→V, then G~V(u,v)=G~U(ϕ(u),ϕ(v)). As a consequence,

{FV+(u,v)=FU+(ϕ(u),ϕ(v))ϕ′(v),FV−(u,v)=FU−(ϕ(u),ϕ(v))ϕ′(v)―.

For instance, for rectangle we have K−1(v1,v2)=∑λk−1fk(v1)fk(v2). Here K=∑λkfk⋅fkT is the polar decomposition with orthonormalised eigenvectors {fk}. Then

K−1(v1,v2)=∑s=1m∑t=1nsin⁡πsΔxm+1⋅sin⁡πtΔyn+12cos⁡πsm+1+2icos⁡πtn+1=14π2∬S1×S1eiΔxθ+iΔyϕ2isin⁡θ−2sin⁡ϕdθdϕ.

Here (Δx,Δy)=(v2−v1)∈Z2​. As a result,

K−1(w,b)={Re1π(b−w)+o(|b−w|−1)(w,b)∈W0×B0,iIm1π(b−w)+o(|b−w|−1)(w,b)∈W0×B1,Re1π(w−b)+o(|b−w|−1)(w,b)∈W1×B0,iIm1π(w−w)+o(|b−w|−1)(w,b)∈W1×B1.

Which coincides the Schwarz-Christoffel transformation.
